{
    "publish_date": "2013-03-07T16:06:39.000Z", 
    "video_length": "PT4M13S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "When we think about learning,", 
            "dur": "1.488", 
            "start": "14.216"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "we often picture students in a classroom or lecture hall,", 
            "dur": "2.661", 
            "start": "15.704"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "books open on their desks,", 
            "dur": "1.308", 
            "start": "18.365"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "listening intently to a teacher or professor", 
            "dur": "2.268", 
            "start": "19.673"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in the front of the room.", 
            "dur": "1.658", 
            "start": "21.941"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But in psychology, learning means something else.", 
            "dur": "2.912", 
            "start": "23.599"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "To psychologists, learning is a long-term change in behavior", 
            "dur": "3.641", 
            "start": "26.511"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that&#39;s based on experience.", 
            "dur": "2.131", 
            "start": "30.152"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Two of the main types of learning are called", 
            "dur": "2.096", 
            "start": "32.283"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "classical conditioning", 
            "dur": "1.642", 
            "start": "34.379"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and operant, or instrumental, conditioning.", 
            "dur": "3.045", 
            "start": "36.021"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Let&#39;s talk about classical conditioning first.", 
            "dur": "2.903", 
            "start": "39.066"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In the 1890&#39;s, a Russian physiologist named Ivan Pavlov", 
            "dur": "3.536", 
            "start": "41.969"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "did some really famous experiments on dogs.", 
            "dur": "2.899", 
            "start": "45.505"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "He showed dogs some food", 
            "dur": "1.332", 
            "start": "48.404"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and rang a bell at the same time.", 
            "dur": "2.044", 
            "start": "49.736"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "After a while, the dogs would associate the bell with the food.", 
            "dur": "3.51", 
            "start": "51.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "They would learn that when they heard the bell,", 
            "dur": "1.652", 
            "start": "55.29"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "they would get fed.", 
            "dur": "1.478", 
            "start": "56.942"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Eventually, just ringing the bell", 
            "dur": "2.034", 
            "start": "58.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "made the dogs salivate.", 
            "dur": "1.461", 
            "start": "60.454"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "They learned to expect food at the sound of a bell.", 
            "dur": "3.546", 
            "start": "61.915"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You see, under normal conditions,", 
            "dur": "2.103", 
            "start": "65.461"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the sight and smell of food causes a dog to salivate.", 
            "dur": "3.451", 
            "start": "67.564"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "We call the food an unconditioned stimulus,", 
            "dur": "2.55", 
            "start": "71.015"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and we call salivation the unconditioned response.", 
            "dur": "3.999", 
            "start": "73.565"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Nobody trains a dog to salivate over some steak.", 
            "dur": "3.468", 
            "start": "77.564"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "However, when we pair an unconditioned stimulus like food", 
            "dur": "3.281", 
            "start": "81.032"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with something that was previously neutral,", 
            "dur": "2.321", 
            "start": "84.313"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "like the sound of a bell,", 
            "dur": "1.568", 
            "start": "86.634"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that neutral stimulus becomes a conditioned stimulus.", 
            "dur": "3.256", 
            "start": "88.202"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And so classical conditioning was discovered.", 
            "dur": "3.628", 
            "start": "91.458"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "We see how this works with animals,", 
            "dur": "2.377", 
            "start": "95.086"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but how does it work with humans?", 
            "dur": "2.125", 
            "start": "97.463"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In exactly the same way.", 
            "dur": "1.817", 
            "start": "99.588"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Let&#39;s say that one day you go to the doctor to get a shot.", 
            "dur": "3.406", 
            "start": "101.405"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "She says, &quot;Don&#39;t worry, this won&#39;t hurt a bit,&quot;", 
            "dur": "2.955", 
            "start": "104.811"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and then gives you the most painful shot you&#39;ve ever had.", 
            "dur": "4.169", 
            "start": "107.766"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "A few weeks later you go to the dentist for a check-up.", 
            "dur": "2.921", 
            "start": "111.935"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "He starts to put a mirror in your mouth", 
            "dur": "1.552", 
            "start": "114.856"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to examine your teeth,", 
            "dur": "1.451", 
            "start": "116.408"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and he says, &quot;Don&#39;t worry, this won&#39;t hurt a bit.&quot;", 
            "dur": "3.465", 
            "start": "117.859"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Even though you know the mirror won&#39;t hurt,", 
            "dur": "2.423", 
            "start": "121.324"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you jump out of the chair and run,", 
            "dur": "1.448", 
            "start": "123.747"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "screaming from the room.", 
            "dur": "1.729", 
            "start": "125.195"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "When you went to get a shot,", 
            "dur": "1.68", 
            "start": "126.924"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the words, &quot;This won&#39;t hurt a bit,&quot;", 
            "dur": "2.248", 
            "start": "128.604"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "became a conditioned stimulus", 
            "dur": "1.615", 
            "start": "130.852"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when they were paired with pain of the shot,", 
            "dur": "2.161", 
            "start": "132.467"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the unconditioned stimulus,", 
            "dur": "2.009", 
            "start": "134.628"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which was followed by your conditioned response", 
            "dur": "2.161", 
            "start": "136.637"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of getting the heck out of there.", 
            "dur": "2.472", 
            "start": "138.798"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Classical conditioning in action.", 
            "dur": "2.738", 
            "start": "141.27"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Operant conditioning explains how consequences", 
            "dur": "2.259", 
            "start": "144.008"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "lead to changes in voluntary behavior.", 
            "dur": "2.875", 
            "start": "146.267"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So how does operant conditioning work?", 
            "dur": "2.336", 
            "start": "149.142"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There are two main components in operant conditioning:", 
            "dur": "3.252", 
            "start": "151.478"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "reinforcement and punishment.", 
            "dur": "2.259", 
            "start": "154.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Reinforcers make it more likely", 
            "dur": "1.788", 
            "start": "156.989"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that you&#39;ll do something again,", 
            "dur": "1.748", 
            "start": "158.777"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "while punishers make it less likely.", 
            "dur": "2.183", 
            "start": "160.525"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Reinforcement and punishment can be positive or negative,", 
            "dur": "3.161", 
            "start": "162.708"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but this doesn&#39;t mean good and bad.", 
            "dur": "2.265", 
            "start": "165.869"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Positive means the addition of a stimulus,", 
            "dur": "2.356", 
            "start": "168.134"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "like getting dessert after you finish your veggies,", 
            "dur": "2.461", 
            "start": "170.49"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and negative means the removal of a stimulus,", 
            "dur": "2.313", 
            "start": "172.951"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "like getting a night of no homework", 
            "dur": "1.701", 
            "start": "175.264"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because you did well on an exam.", 
            "dur": "2.504", 
            "start": "176.965"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Let&#39;s look at an example of operant conditioning.", 
            "dur": "2.707", 
            "start": "179.469"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "After eating dinner with your family,", 
            "dur": "1.819", 
            "start": "182.176"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you clear the table and wash the dishes.", 
            "dur": "2.527", 
            "start": "183.995"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "When you&#39;re done, your mom gives you a big hug", 
            "dur": "2.202", 
            "start": "186.522"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and says, &quot;Thank you for helping me.&quot;", 
            "dur": "2.384", 
            "start": "188.724"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In this situation, your mom&#39;s response", 
            "dur": "2.159", 
            "start": "191.108"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is positive reinforcement if it makes you more likely", 
            "dur": "2.629", 
            "start": "193.267"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to repeat the operant response,", 
            "dur": "1.793", 
            "start": "195.896"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which is to clear the table and wash the dishes.", 
            "dur": "2.922", 
            "start": "197.689"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Operant conditioning is everywhere in our daily lives.", 
            "dur": "3.427", 
            "start": "200.611"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There aren&#39;t many things we do", 
            "dur": "1.495", 
            "start": "204.038"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that haven&#39;t been influenced at some point", 
            "dur": "1.94", 
            "start": "205.533"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by operant conditioning.", 
            "dur": "1.835", 
            "start": "207.473"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "We even see operant conditioning", 
            "dur": "1.772", 
            "start": "209.308"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in some extraordinary situations.", 
            "dur": "3.041", 
            "start": "211.08"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "One group of scientists showed the power", 
            "dur": "2.34", 
            "start": "214.121"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of operant conditioning", 
            "dur": "1.04", 
            "start": "216.461"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by teaching pigeons to be art connoisseurs.", 
            "dur": "2.889", 
            "start": "217.501"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Using food as a positive reinforcer,", 
            "dur": "2.335", 
            "start": "220.39"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "scientists have taught pigeons", 
            "dur": "1.417", 
            "start": "222.725"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to select paintings by Monet", 
            "dur": "2.25", 
            "start": "224.142"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "over those by Picasso.", 
            "dur": "1.996", 
            "start": "226.392"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "When showed works of other artists,", 
            "dur": "2.256", 
            "start": "228.388"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "scientists observed stimulus generalization", 
            "dur": "2.792", 
            "start": "230.644"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "as the pigeons chose the Impressionists", 
            "dur": "1.793", 
            "start": "233.436"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "over the Cubists.", 
            "dur": "1.525", 
            "start": "235.229"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Maybe next they&#39;ll condition the pigeons", 
            "dur": "1.855", 
            "start": "236.754"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to paint their own masterpieces.", 
            "dur": "1.926", 
            "start": "238.609"
        }
    ], 
